04124nam a2200661Ia 9780271096162DE-B159720240602123719.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240602t20242024pau    fo  d z      eng d  a9780271096162  a(DE-B1597)691418  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aND2861.8.Z9bQ29 2024 7aART0151002bisacsh04a751.7/309611223/eng/202308071 aGallois, William, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aQayrawān :bThe Amuletic City /cWilliam Gallois. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2024] 4c©2024  a1 online resource (208 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRefiguring Modernism00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tEditorial Note -- tIntroduction: A Twofold Mystery -- t1. The Occupation of Qayrawān -- t2. Visual Archaeology -- t3. Bab Lalla Rihana -- t4. The Mosque -- t5. Inversion, Ambience -- t6. You -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the last years of the nineteenth century, the Tunisian city of Qayrawān suddenly found itself covered in murals. Concentrated on and around the city’s Great Mosque, these monumental artworks were only visible for about fifty years, from the 1880s through the 1930s. This book investigates the fascinating history of who created these outdoor paintings and why.Using visual archaeological methods, William Gallois reconstructs the visual history of these works and vividly brings them back to life. He locates pictorial records of the murals from the backdrops of photographs, postcards, and other forms of European ephemera. In Qayrawān, he identifies a form of religious painting that transposed traditional aesthetic forms such as house decoration, embroidery, and tattooing—which lay exclusively within the domains of women—onto the body of a conquered city. Gallois argues that these works were created by women as a form of “emergency art,” intended to offer amuletic protection for the community, and demonstrates how they differ markedly from “classical” Islamic antecedents and modern modes of Arab cultural production in the Middle East and North Africa.Based on extensive archival research, this study is both a record of a unique moment in the history of art and a challenge to rethink the spiritual force and agency of a group of anonymous female artists whose paintings aspired to help save the world at a time of great peril. It will be welcomed by scholars of art history, Islamic studies, Middle East studies, and the history of magic.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aMural painting and decorationzTunisiazQayrawāny19th century. 0aPhotography of art. 0aSymbolism in art. 0aWomen artistszTunisiazQayrawānxHistoryy19th century. 7aART / History / Modern (late 19th Century to 1945).2bisacsh  aArt history.  aArt.  aHistory of art.  aHistory.  aIslam.  aIslamic History.  aKairouan.  aMaghreb.  aMurals.  aNorth Africa.  aPainting.  aQayrawān.  aTunisia.  aWomen.40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271096162423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271096162/original  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles